To FanFiction or Not To FanFiction

Posted on February 26, 2015 by Monica McGurk 


		 All of the recent commentary on Fifty Shades of Grey has once again stirred the pot on the value and role of fan fiction in the literary world. Most of the commentary, including this article in The Daily Beast,  has addressed this question from the viewpoint of the traditional publishing world (e.g., how can we monetize this vast pool of creativity?), or that of the original titles’ authors (e.g., do I or do I not support this use of my work?).
 I, for one, love lawyer Rebecca Tushnet’s commentary (speaking to those writers who worry about copyright infringement) that it is clearly not good business to sue your fans! In my day job, my colleagues and I spend countless hours talking about the level of engagement consumers have with our brands. Can you imagine how engaged a reader must be to want to dive back deep into the world you have created and keep telling your story? Never mind that it is a prequel, sequel or AU — they want to spend more time with the characters you have created, and I think that is a lovely thing. I personally would give my right eye tooth to have readers love my work that much.
 Another viewpoint to consider is that of the aspiring writer. Is it easier to write fan fiction? Yes. It is, even if marginally so, because there is some framework already given you — characters, former storylines, settings — from which you can riff. But the rich variations evident on sites like fanfiction.net should illustrate that this is a slight advantage — the creativity displayed in fan fiction knows no bounds and writers can use the medium to craft what in the end feels like truly original work, even if working off of the structure of stories that have come before. What was more relevant to me as I re-engaged in writing was that the infrastructure around fan fiction meant I had the means to get instant feedback on my writing, reviews pouring in as I posted each chapter, and an eager fan base that was already primed to read what I was writing even though, to them, I was an anonymous nobody. I took it seriously and I used it as a vehicle not just to pay homage, but to hone my craft. And the bar was high — believe me.  People reading fan fiction are the most loyal readers on Earth.  They know these worlds inside and out.  They know every last detail of how the universe their beloved characters inhabit are supposed to work.  They have memorized every like and dislike, every facial tic and tell, their favorite characters exhibit.  They care passionately about these stories.  So, as a writer of Fan Fiction, you’d better bring your A Game or be subjected to merciless criticism.
 If you want to improve your writing skills, how could that be wrong?
 It is an easy thing to dismiss fan fiction as low brow. Guess what? Much of pop culture is. Democratization of cultural expression often provokes such responses. I, for one, am glad that the growth of the Internet and Social Media has made this form of self-expression accessible and thank the readers who cheered me on as I took advantage of it.
			






  



Monica McGurk






