Her first novel is a young adult thriller in the tradition of the “Twilight” series. — Submitted 





























































Monica Houle McGurk is a 1988 graduate of Forest Lake High School, currently living in Atlanta.  — Submitted 















































































        
        Hugo native tops business career with new novel
    


By Michelle Miron


Aug 7, 2014
 0


























































Her first novel is a young adult thriller in the tradition of the “Twilight” series. — Submitted 



























Monica Houle McGurk is a 1988 graduate of Forest Lake High School, currently living in Atlanta.  — Submitted 




























































ATLANTA, Georgia — She’s earned her way to a high-powered career in business, but Monica Houle McGurk’s most recent accomplishment is something completely creative.On July 28 the Hugo native and 1988 graduate of Forest Lake Area High School, releases her first novel “Dark Hope,” a young adult thriller in the tradition of the “Twilight” series about love between an archangel and a human being. Next on her agenda: two sequels to the trilogy.Now living in Atlanta, and working as head of strategy and e-commerce for Coca Cola’s North America Group, the 44-year-old McGurk said it was a former colleague’s untimely death several years ago that made her realize she had creative aspirations beyond her day job and parenthood.
“You never really know when your time’s going to be up,” she noted. “Earlier in my life I had dabbled a little in writing, so I thought I’d start writing again, maybe squeezing it in on plane trips and quiet times late at night.”In spite of the requisite rejections from other publishers, her efforts paid off when Greenleaf Book Group gave her the thumbs-up.The mom of three said FLAHS classmates may remember her as “smart but a little geeky” because she participated so heavily in speech, debate and theater (she credits former teachers and coaches Deb Bendix, Dorothy Sunne and Jane Gilles for her critical thinking and public speaking skills). McGurk now holds a B.A. from Harvard and both an M.A. and an MBA from Stanford, while her past resume includes management jobs at Deluxe Corp., the Ohio Chamber Orchestra, General Mills and Stanford. For 19 years she worked for Minneapolis management consulting firm McKinsey & Co., becoming partner before leaving two years ago to join Coca-Cola.In between those jobs she founded The Alumni Factor, a college evaluation system that ranks schools on real-world outcomes.She and her husband Tom have three children: Son Trey, 14; daughter Reagan, 12; and son John Patrick, 8.McGurk’s role at Coca Cola these days involves strategizing and decision-making — usually three to four years ahead —  about how to best use resources and maximize markets to drive volume growth.Once she decided to start writing fiction, her first work was a fan fiction piece that presented an alternative ending to Stephanie Meyer’s “Twilight” series she titled “Morning Star.” The positive feedback she received after posting it on sciencefiction.net (and winning the 2013 Twific Fandom “Undiscovered Gem” award) encouraged her to post her prequel to the series called “Rosalie’s Revenge” and then start work on “Dark Hope.”Paranormal themes and the young adult genre seemed a natural fit to the fan of the Harry Potter series.“I talked to a few writers, and kind of approached it as a puzzle,” she said. “A lot of the (career) work I do is problem solving big hairy issues,  and to be figuring out plot and character is all a big problem-solving exercise.” A physician friend advised her on medical issues in the plot, while a contact from Las Vegas gave her tips about the gaming industry.“It was really kind of neat to dive into these worlds and go places not everyone has gone,” she noted.In spite of her past career success, she said she’s somewhat daunted to hear reactions to the book, and she’s self-critical of some of her own writing.“There’s always the trepidation of putting yourself out there,” she said. “You have to be prepared for people to hate it, as much as you would want them to love it.”
Next up, she’s completing two other novels in the “Dark Hope” series to which the publisher has already committed. The next one, now being edited, is partly set in Europe and involves historical artifacts in a nod toward Dan Brown thrillers.The process also involved research into real-life issues in which McGurk has made something of a platform: human trafficking and child exploitation.“I was really shocked to find there really is an active trade in the United States,” she said. “I had no idea Atlanta is one of the biggest places for (human trafficking) in the U.S., and once you learn about it you can’t turn away, it’s such a horrific thing.”Since then she’s joined the advisory board and speakers’ bureau of Norcross, Georgia-based organization Street Grace, which works to raise awareness of such issues.  A portion of revenues from the “Dark Hope” trilogy will be donated to the nonprofit.  In her spare time she likes to run, travel with her family and volunteer through her church. She only occasionally gets back to Minnesota, as her parents have moved to Arizona.  Becoming a full-time writer is probably not in the cards for McGurk.“I really have enjoyed my career in business,” she noted. “It was never really planned, I kind of fell into it, but I still enjoy it. And it’s now normal to have lots of different careers in your life at the same time. People put a lot of pressure on themselves to know what they want to do when they go to school, but I think it’s OK to not know, to explore or change your mind because you’re discovering something new and fascinating.”Michelle Miron is editor of the Forest Lake Lowdown





















































